  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What are the standard puzzles asked in programming interviews?",
  "response": "During programming interviews, a variety of standard puzzles are commonly asked to assess candidates' problem-solving skills and coding ability. Here are some of the well-known puzzles that you might encounter:\n\n1. **Two-Sum Problem**:\n   - Given an array of integers and a target sum, find two numbers in the array that add up to the target sum. Return their indices.\n\n2. **Reverse a Linked List**:\n   - Given a singly linked list, reverse the list and return the new head.\n\n3. **Merge Two Sorted Lists**:\n   - Given two sorted linked lists, merge them into one sorted linked list.\n\n4. **Palindrome Check**:\n   - Determine if a given string is a palindrome (it reads the same forward and backward).\n\n5. **Nth Fibonacci Number**:\n   - Calculate the Nth number in the Fibonacci sequence.\n\n6. **Sorting Algorithms**:\n   - Implement common sorting algorithms like Quick Sort, Merge Sort, or Bubble Sort.\n\n7. **Binary Search**:\n   - Given a sorted array, implement binary search to find the position of a target value.\n\n8. **Find the Loop in a Linked List**:\n   - Determine if a linked list has a cycle, and find the starting node of the cycle if it exists.\n\n9. **Maximum Subarray (Kadane's Algorithm)**:\n   - Given an array of integers, find the contiguous subarray with the maximum sum.\n\n10. **String Matching**:\n    - Implement algorithms for string matching like Knuth-Morris-Pratt or Rabin-Karp to find all occurrences of a substring in a longer string.\n\n11. **Anagram Check**:\n    - Determine if two strings are anagrams of each other.\n\n12. **Balanced Parentheses**:\n    - Given a string containing just the characters '(', ')', '{', '}', '[' and ']', determine if the input string is valid (i.e., all open brackets are closed by the same type of brackets).\n\n13. **Median of Two Sorted Arrays**:\n    - Given two sorted arrays, find the median of the two arrays combined.\n\n14. **Subtree Check**:\n    - Check if one binary tree is a subtree of another binary tree.\n\n15. **Rotate Matrix**:\n    - Given a 2D matrix, rotate it 90 degrees clockwise.\n\n16. **Deep Copy of a Graph**:\n    - Clone a graph, assuming each node has neighbors represented as a list.\n\n17. **Longest Common Subsequence**:\n    - Find the longest subsequence common to two sequences.\n\n18. **Coin Change Problem**:\n    - Given a set of coin denominations and a target amount, find the minimum number of coins required to make that amount.\n\n19. **Intersection of Two Linked Lists**:\n    - Determine where two singly linked lists intersect.\n\n20. **LRU Cache Implementation**:\n    - Design and implement an LRU (Least Recently Used) cache with O(1) operations for get and put.\n\nThese puzzles can range from easier to more complex problems, often involving data structures like arrays, strings, linked lists, trees, graphs, and various algorithms. Solving them typically requires a clear understanding of fundamental coding concepts, efficient algorithm design, and sometimes, the ability to discuss and explain the approach during the interview.",
